{{Expand Chinese|卡那卡那富族|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = Kanakanavu | native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh|卡那卡那富}}}} | total = ~338 | total_year = June 2018 | popplace = [[Taiwan]] | langs = [[Kanakanavu language|Kanakanavu]], [[Bunun language|Bunun]], [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]], [[Taiwanese Hokkien]] | rels = [[Animism]], [[Christianity]] | related = [[Tsou people|Tsou]], [[Bunun people|Bunun]], [[Saaroa people|Saaroa]], [[Taiwanese Aborigines]] }}
The '''Kanakanavu''' ({{zh|c=卡那卡那富|p=|w=Kanakanavu}}) are an indigenous people of central southern [[Taiwan]]. They live in the two villages of Manga and Takanua in [[Namasia District]], [[Kaohsiung]] City, Taiwan (Zeitoun & Teng 2014). <ref>{{cite web |url=http://iscll-14.ling.sinica.edu.tw/files-pdf/Papers/Session6/ZeitounTeng.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606223817/http://iscll-14.ling.sinica.edu.tw/files-pdf/Papers/Session6/ZeitounTeng.pdf |archivedate=2014-06-06 |df= }}</ref>
== History == The native Kanakanavu speakers were [[Taiwanese aboriginals]] living on the islands. Following the [[Dutch Formosa|Dutch Colonial Period]] in the 17th century, [[Han-Chinese]] immigration began to dominate the islands population. The village of [[Takanua]] is a village assembled by [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese rulers]] to relocate various aboriginal groups in order to establish easier dominion over these groups.<ref>https://www2.uni-erfurt.de/sprachwissenschaft/Vgl_SW/kanakanavu/language-description/setting-of-language/ethnographic-situation.html https://www2.uni-erfurt.de/sprachwissenschaft/Vgl_SW/kanakanavu/language-description/setting-of-language/ethnographic-situation.html</ref>
On 26 June 2014, the government recognized Kanakanavu as the 16th group of [[Taiwanese aborigines|Taiwanese indigenous]].<ref>http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/national/national-news/2014/06/27/411066/Govt-officially.htm</ref>
=== Livelihood === Japanese occupation left evidence of how the culture functioned. Forest clearance allowed agriculture to be the main facet of society, followed by hunting and fishing. [[Maize]], Rice, [[Millet]], [[Taro]], Sweet Potatoes, beans, and soybeans were the staple crops.<ref>https://www2.uni-erfurt.de/sprachwissenschaft/Vgl_SW/kanakanavu/language-description/setting-of-language/cultural-situation.html https://www2.uni-erfurt.de/sprachwissenschaft/Vgl_SW/kanakanavu/language-description/setting-of-language/cultural-situation.html</ref>
=== Spirituality === Kanakanavu practiced a [[polytheistic]] nature religion involving offerings, fertility rituals, and [[shamanism]]. [[Headhunting]] was a common practice until Christianization took over.<ref>https://www2.uni-erfurt.de/sprachwissenschaft/Vgl_SW/kanakanavu/language-description/setting-of-language/social-situation.html https://www2.uni-erfurt.de/sprachwissenschaft/Vgl_SW/kanakanavu/language-description/setting-of-language/social-situation.html</ref>
