The '''United Party''' was a [[political party]] in [[the Gambia]]. The party was founded during the colonial period and worked political in the then colony of [[Banjul|Bathurst]] (the present capital of the Gambia, Banjul).<ref name="code">{{Cite web |url=http://www.codesria.org/Links/Publications/ad3_2000/edie.pdf |title=Democracy in The Gambia by Carlene J Edie<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2008-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927164212/http://www.codesria.org/Links/Publications/ad3_2000/edie.pdf |archive-date=2006-09-27 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> The party drew support mainly from [[Roman Catholics]].<ref>[http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/2007/11/11/encounter-with-oko-drammeh Encounter with Oko Drammeh - Daily Observer<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In Banjul it had support mainly amongst the [[Wolof people|Wolof]]s, in the rural areas mainly amongst [[Fula people|Fula]]s.<ref name="code"/> The party was led by [[Pierre Sarr N'Jie|P. S. Njie]].<ref>[http://www.thepoint.gm/art%20&%20C,%20TT,%20E%20&%20W167.htm Arts and Culture<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
In 1963, the [[People's Progressive Party (Gambia)|People's Progressive Party]] and DCA invited UP to join the government. After two years, the party left the government. Its position as an opposition party had declined, though. In 1970, the party suffered a heavy blow as its leader joined the PPP.<ref name="code"/>
During the 1970s and 1980s the party strongly opposed a union with [[Senegal]].<ref>http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/arc/GAMBIA_1977_E.PDF</ref>
